tegory:Fictional Bronze Star recipients]]\n[[Category:Fictional Silver Star recipients]]\n[[Category:Fictional United States Navy SEALs personnel]]\n[[Category:Fictional War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present) veterans]]\n[[Category:Hawaii Five-O]]\n\n[[fr:Steve McGarrett]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2016}}\n'''Steve McGarrett''' is a fictional character who is the protagonist of [[CBS]]' ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]''. McGarrett is a former [[United States Navy]] officer and the leader of a special state police task force, which is called Five-O. McGarrett was famously portrayed by [[Jack Lord]] in the original show from 1968 to 1980, and later by [[Alex O'Loughlin]] in the [[Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|series' remake]] beginning in 2010. Throughout the show, McGarrett is partner to Detective Danny \"Danno\" Williams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/features/five-0-redux/five-0-redux-mcgarrett-danno/|title=For the love of McGarrett and Danno|accessdate=May 17, 2016|date=August 30, 2014|work=[[Honolulu Star Advertiser]]|author=Burbridge, Wendie}}</ref>\n\n==''Hawaii Five-0'' (1968\u201380)==\n{{Infobox character\n| colour           = \n| name             = Steve McGarrett\n| series           = <!-- use without the italic on the outside -->\n| image            = Jack Lord Hawaii Five-O.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| first            = \"[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series, season 1)#ep1|Cocoon]]\"<br />(episode 1.01)\n| last             = [[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series, season 12)#ep19|Woe to Wo Fat]]<br />(episode 12.19)\n| creator          = [[Leonard Freeman]]\n| portrayer        = [[Jack Lord]]\n| voice            = \n| lbl1             = \n| data1            = \n| lbl2             = \n| data2            = \n| lbl3             = \n| data3            = \n| info-hdr         = \n| noinfo           = \n| full_name         = \n| nickname         = \n| alias            = \n| occupation       = Head of Five-0 Task Force<br />Former [[United States Navy]] Lieutenant \n| title            = Detective Captain\n| family           = Mary Ann Whalen (sister)\n| spouse           = \n| significant_other =  \n| relatives        = Tom Whalen (brother-in-law)\n| religion         = \n}}\nIn the [[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|original show]], Steve McGarrett was portrayed by [[Jack Lord]] from 1968 to 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/jan/23/news/mn-11328|title=Jack Lord, Star of 'Hawaii Five-0,' Dies|accessdate=May 30, 2016|date=January 23, 1998|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Oliver, Myrna}}</ref> McGarrett was a former [[United States Navy]] Lieutenant and Detective Captain in the [[Honolulu Police Department]] who had been requested by Governor Paul Jameson to head the Five-0 Task Force, a fictional equivalent of the [[state police]]. He was portrayed as a highly driven cop and workaholic, often staying at his office until midnight. It was said that he \"only takes orders from the Governor and God \u2013 and occasionally even they have trouble\".<ref>{{cite episode |title=Cocoon|episodelink=Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series, season 1)#ep1|series=Hawaii Five-O|serieslink=Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=September 20, 1968|season=1|number=1}}</ref>\n\nMcGarrett had a sister Mary Ann ([[Nancy Malone]]).<ref>{{cite episode |title=Once Upon a Time: Part 1|episodelink=Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series, season 1)|series=Hawaii Five-O|serieslink=Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=February 19, 1969|season=1|number=20}}</ref> Their mother was murdered by criminals when they were young. It was revealed that this personal tragedy was what motivated McGarrett to become a police officer.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Number One with a Bullet: Part 2|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (season 11)#ep252|series=Hawaii Five-O|serieslink=Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=January 4, 1979|season=11|number=13}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode |title=Number One with a Bullet: Part 1|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (season 11)#ep251|series=Hawaii Five-O|serieslink=Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=December 28, 1978|season=11|number=12}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the series he drives a black Mercury; a 1967 2-door  [[Mercury Marquis]] hardtop with a red interior in the pilot only,<ref>http://www.imcdb.org/vehicle_88376-Mercury-Marquis-1967.html</ref> followed by a 1968 4-door [[Mercury Park Lane]] Brougham hardtop,<ref>http://www.imcdb.org/vehicle_174370-Mercury-Park-Lane-Brougham-1968.html</ref> then ultimately a 1974 4-door [[Mercury Marquis]] Brougham hardtop in subsequent episodes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tonight's 'Hawaii Five-0' includes original's Mercury Marquis|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2010/09/tonights-hawaii-five-0-includes-originals-mercury-marquis/1|accessdate=March 9, 2011|date=September 20, 2010|work=USA Today|first=Chris|last=Woodyard}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==''Hawaii Five-0'' (2010\u2013present)==\n{{Infobox character\n| colour           = \n| name             = Steve McGarrett<br><span style=\"font-size:75%;\">[[George Cross|GC]]</span><ref>https://m.imdb.com/title/tt5933002/goofs</ref> \n| series           = <!-- use without the italic on the outside -->\n| image            = Ritchson and Olouglin C-17.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| first            = [[Pilot (Hawaii Five-0)|Pilot]]<br />(episode 1.01)\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Leonard Freeman]]<br />[[Peter M. Lenkov]]\n| portrayer        = [[Alex O'Loughlin]]\n| voice            = \n| lbl1             = \n| data1            = \n| lbl2             = \n| data2            = \n| lbl3             = \n| data3            = \n| info-hdr         = \n| noinfo           = \n| full_name         = Steven J McGarrett\n| nickname         = Stevie (by Aunt Deb)<br>Smooth Dog<ref name=\"SuperSEAL\"/><br>McGruff\n| alias            = \n| occupation       = Head of Five-0 Task Force;<br>[[United States Navy Reserve|USNR]];<br>[[United States Navy]] (former)\n| title            = [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]]\n| family           = John McGarrett (father;<ref name=Sds>{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/features/five-0-redux/seven-deadly-sins/|title=Seven deadly sins|accessdate=May 17, 2016|date=November 27, 2015|work=[[Honolulu Star Advertiser]]|author=Burbridge, Wendie}}</ref> deceased)<br>Doris McGarrett (mother,deceased)<br>Mary Ann McGarrett (sister)<br>Steven McGarrett (grandfather; deceased)<br>Joan McGarrett (niece)\n| spouse           = \n| significant_other = [[List of Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series) characters#Catherine  Rollins|Catherine Rollins]] (ex-girlfriend)<br>[[list of Hawaii five-0 (2010 TV series) characters#Lynn Downey|Lynn Downey]] (ex-girlfriend)<br>[[list of Hawaii five-0 (2010 TV series) characters#Greer|Greer]] (ex- girlfriend)<br>Brooke (ex-girlfriend)<br>Dr Okino(girlfriend)\n| children         =\n| relatives        = Deborah \"Deb\" McGarrett (aunt) (deceased)<!--<br>Joan McGarrett (niece)--> \n| religion         = \n}}\nAustralian actor [[Alex O'Loughlin]] portrays Steve McGarrett in the [[Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|2010 remake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/20/entertainment/la-et-hawaii-five-20100920|title=Television review: 'Hawaii Five-0'|accessdate=May 30, 2016|date=September 20, 2010|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=McNamara, Mary}}</ref> The current incarnation bears some similarities to [[Jack Lord]]'s character, such as their Navy Intelligence background and a long-standing nemesis in [[Wo Fat]].\n\nIn the pilot episode, Lieutenant Commander Steven J. \"Steve\" McGarrett was in [[South Korea]] on a classified mission escorting wanted arms dealer Anton Hesse when he received a call via [[satellite phone]] from his father John and finds out that Anton's brother Victor was coincidentally holding John hostage on an unrelated matter. McGarrett's convoy was attacked by a helicopter of armed men trying to rescue Anton, resulting in Anton being killed. When Victor finds out, he shoots John point blank with the younger McGarrett still on the line.<ref name=HF2>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Hawaii-Five-0-2-0-Love-it-or-leave-it-2462207.php|title=Hawaii Five-0 2.0: Love it or leave it?|accessdate=May 10, 2016|date=September 21, 2010|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|author=Yang, Jeff}}</ref> McGarrett returns to Hawaii to bury his father and is asked by Governor Jameson to set up a task force with \"full immunity and means\" to investigate and capture criminals such as the Hesse brothers.<ref name=HF>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2010/09/17/hawaii-five-0-a-slick-expensive-vacation-from-tv-ambition/|title=Hawaii Five-0: Broadcast Takes a Vacation from Ambition|accessdate=May 10, 2016|date=September 17, 2010|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|author=Poniewozik, James}}</ref> Despite his initial hesitation, he eventually agrees and transfers to the [[United States Navy Reserve]]. He then recruits [[Newark Police Department (New Jersey)|Newark PD]] transfer, [[List of Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series) characters#Danny Williams|Detective Sergeant Danny \"Danno\" Williams]], his father's former trainee [[List of Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series) characters#Chin Ho Kelly|Lieutenant Chin Ho Kelly]] and recent HPD Academy graduate [[List of Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series) characters#Kono Kalakaua|Officer Kono Kalakaua]]. These four make up the original members of the \"Governor's Task Force\", later renamed \"Five-0\".  When McGarrett assembles his task force, he partners with Williams.<ref name=HF/><ref name=SCHLoHF>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/scott-caan-hawaii-1025210/|title=Scott Caan Hangs Loose on Hawaii Five-0|accessdate=May 10, 2016|date=November 8, 2010|work=[[TV Guide]]|author=Keck, William}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/hawaii-five-0-returns-to-tv/|title='Hawaii Five-0' Returns to TV|accessdate=May 10, 2016|date=May 20, 2010|publisher=[[CBS News]]|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Background===\nSince returning to Hawaii, McGarrett has lived in his childhood home at 2727 Piikoi Street along the beach, where his father continued to live in after the break-up of his family and was murdered.<ref name=\"Tributes\">{{cite news|title=Hawaii Five-0 Hidden Tributes to Original Series|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/hawaii_five_0/news/1003388/hawaii-five-0-hidden-tributes-to-original-series-100th-episode/|publisher=[[CBS]]|date=October 30, 2014}}</ref> Although technically a ''[[haole]]'' like Danny, Steve is accepted as ''[[kama'aina]]'' as he was not only born in [[Hawaii]], but was raised to respect and embrace the local culture.<ref>{{cite web|title=Five-0 Redux: Casting the 'Five-0' \u2018ohana|url=http://www.honolulupulse.com/2015/06/five-0-ohana/|publisher=Honolulu Pulse ([[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]])|date=June 6, 2015}}</ref> In several episodes, he is shown to be conversant in \"bird\" ([[Hawaiian Pidgin]]).<ref name=\"Pilot\"/><ref>{{cite episode |title=Ko\u02bbolauloa / North Shore of O\u02bbahu|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 1)#ep6|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=October 25, 2010|season=1|number=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode |title=Heihei / Race|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 1)#ep10|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=November 22, 2010|season=1|number=10}}</ref> As such, he was not antagonized as much as Danny was by the locals during the first several seasons, evidenced by his friendship with [[List of Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series) characters#Mamo Kahike|Mamo]] and the deference shown to him even by ''Kapu'' leader Kawika and [[List of Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series) characters#Kamekona Tupuola|Kamekona]], who affectionately calls McGarrett \"the big [[kahuna]]\".{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nBased on McGarrett's [[Flashback (narrative)|flashback]]s and statements from other characters, he had a happy childhood and enjoyed spending time in the garage watching his father fix the antique 1974 [[Mercury Marquis]].<ref name=\"Tributes\"/> He inherited his father's passion for antique cars and occasionally drove the Marquis after fixing it up himself.<ref name=\"Tributes\"/> He was a high school sophomore when his mother Doris<ref name=Sds/> was presumed to be killed in a car accident in April 1992,<ref name=\"S1E11\">{{cite episode |title=Palekaiko / Paradise|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 1)#ep11|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=December 6, 2010|season=1|number=11}}</ref> prompting John to send Steve and his younger sister Mary away to the mainland for their own safety. Steve was sent to boarding school while Mary went to live with John's older sister Deb. With the surfacing of crime lord [[Wo Fat]] and the theft of John's mysterious tool box after Steve's return to Hawaii, the truth behind Doris' \"death\" is gradually revealed; while the siblings reunite with their mother, they are still suspicious of her and consider Aunt Deb to be their maternal figure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/features/five-0-redux/five-0-redux-until-we-meet-again/|title=Until we meet again|accessdate=May 17, 2016|date=May 21, 2013|work=[[Honolulu Star Advertiser]]|author=Burbridge, Wendie}}</ref> Steve is said to be fifteen or sixteen in 1992, putting his birth year in 1976 or 1977, which roughly corresponds with the fact that he was in [[BUD/S]] in the year 2000.<ref name=\"S3E20\">{{cite episode |title=Olelo Pa\u02bba / The Promise|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 3)#ep67|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=April 15, 2013|season=3|number=20}}</ref> A star [[quarterback]], he attended the fictional Kukui High School before being sent to the [[Army and Navy Academy]] in [[California]] for his junior and senior years after the death of his mother. This led to a decade-long period of estrangement between John and his children.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} In the season 6 episode \"[[Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 6)#ep134|Ka Pohaku Kihi Pa'a / The Solid Cornerstone]]\", Steve admitted that he deeply regretted not patching things up with his father when he had the chance to.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n===Military and Five-0===\nMcGarrett is a third-generation Navy veteran and he was named after his late grandfather, Ensign Steven McGarrett, who perished on the [[USS Arizona (BB-39)|USS ''Arizona'']] during the [[attacks on Pearl Harbor]] in December 1941. His grandfather has been referenced a number of times as the younger McGarrett had met a [[Internment of Japanese Americans|Japanese American internee]]<ref>{{cite episode |title=Ho\u02bbonani Makuakane / Honor Thy Father|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 4)#ep81|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=December 13, 2013|season=4|number=10}}</ref> and a retired Petty Officer,<ref name=\"S1E07\"/> both of whom knew Ensign McGarrett when he was still alive. He graduated from the [[United States Naval Academy]] and went on to have a distinguished career. Governor Jameson once outlined his resume: \"Annapolis, five years [[Office of Naval Intelligence|Naval Intelligence]], six years with the [[United States Navy SEALs|SEALs]]. Your superiors say that you are the best they have ever seen.\"<ref name=\"Pilot\">{{cite episode |title=Pilot|episodelink=Pilot (Hawaii Five-0)|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=September 20, 2010|season=1|number=1}}</ref> McGarrett graduated from [[BUD/S]] Class 203 (in real life, Class 203 graduated in 1996, not the 2000s)<ref name=\"S1E07\">{{cite episode |title=Ho\u02bbapono / Accept|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 1)#ep7|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=November 1, 2010|season=1|number=7}}</ref> at the top of his class.<ref name=\"S2E2\">{{cite episode |title=Ua Lawe Wale / Taken|episodelink=Hawaii Five-O (2010 TV series, season 2)|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=September 26, 2011|season=2|number=2}}</ref> His time in the military is largely unknown or vague due to the highly classified nature of most of his missions, but it was mentioned that he has been deployed to [[Afghanistan]],<ref name=\"S1E09\"/> [[Iraq]] and [[North Korea]], served on board the [[USS Enterprise (CVN-65)|USS ''Enterprise'']],<ref name=\"S6E15\">{{cite episode |title=Ke Koa Lokomaika'i / The Good Soldier|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 6)#ep133|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=February 19, 2016|season=1|number=15}}</ref> was stationed at [[Naval Amphibious Base Coronado|Coronado]] at some point in his career<ref name=\"S1E05\">{{cite episode |title=Nalowale / Forgotten/Missing|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 1)#ep5|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=October 18, 2010|season=1|number=5}}</ref> and was known by the nickname \"Smooth Dog\".<ref name=\"S3E20\"/><ref name=\"S1E09\">{{cite episode |title=Po\u02bbipu / The Siege|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 1)#ep9|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=November 15, 2010|season=1|number=9}}</ref> He is multilingual and is mainly conversant in Asian languages; he understands [[Pashto language|Pashto]] (he did several tours in [[Afghanistan]]), speaks<ref name=\"S1E14\">{{cite episode |title=He Kane Hewa\u02bbole / An Innocent Man|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 1)#ep14|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=January 17, 2011|season=1|number=14}}</ref> and reads Mandarin fluently<ref>{{cite episode |title=Hoa Pili / Close Friend|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 3)#ep66|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=March 25, 2013|season=3|number=19}}</ref> and knows conversational Korean<ref name=\"S3E20\"/> and Japanese. He is friends with former Navy SEAL Senior Chief Petty Officer, now [[Naval Criminal Investigative Service|NCIS]] [[Sam Hanna (character)|Special Agent Sam Hanna]] from ''[[NCIS: Los Angeles]]'' and former Delta Force operative turned [[Organizations in MacGyver|Phoenix Foundation]] agent [[List of MacGyver characters|Jack Dalton]] from ''[[MacGyver (2016 TV series)|MacGyver]]''. Due to his background in [[Office of Naval Intelligence|intelligence]] and special ops, he is well-connected to high-ranking officials in the Navy and the [[CIA]], which he has used to his advantage on several occasions.<ref name=\"S4E16\">{{cite episode |title=Hoku Welowelo / Fire in the Sky|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 4)#ep87|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=March 7, 2014|season=4|number=16}}</ref> Prior to his father's murder, he served on a \"black op\" with his best friend, Freddie Hart, but the mission went south and Hart was killed; his body was not recovered until Season 3 when McGarrett personally flew to North Korea to oversee the repatriation.<ref name=\"S3E20\"/> In season 4, he admits to [[List of Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series) characters#Lou Grover|Lou Grover]] that after Hart's death, the Navy \"didn't feel the same\" anymore and that he jumped at the chance to leave when Governor Jameson asked him to set up the task force.<ref name=\"S4E16\"/>\n\nMcGarrett uses the same weapons he used as a SEAL including a [[SIG Sauer P226|P226 Navy]] as his sidearm as well as the [[Heckler & Koch]] [[Heckler & Koch MP5#MP5K|MP5K]] and [[Heckler & Koch MP7|MP7]] sub-machine guns, and [[Heckler & Koch HK416|HK416]] assault rifle. Besides his father's vintage Marquis, McGarrett drives a blue [[Chevrolet Silverado]]. Its license plate registration number is F6-3958, which was also used by Jack Lord's character in the original series.<ref name=\"Tributes\"/>\n\nIn \"No Ke Ali'i' Wahine A Me Ka Aina\", Steve and Danny, along with an MI-6 officer ([[Chris Vance (actor)|Chris Vance]]) are awarded the [[George Cross]] by Queen [[Elizabeth II]] for stopping a terrorist attack against Europe.<ref name=\"S702\">{{cite episode |title=No Ke Ali'i' Wahine A Me Ka Aina / For Queen and Country|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 7)|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=September 30, 2016|season=7|number=2}}</ref>\n\n===Characterization and relationships===\nDespite the fact that he is no longer on full-time active duty, McGarrett's military background and SEAL training are still evident in his daily routine and habits; he still takes a \"[[Navy shower]]\", keeps his house impeccably neat and tidy, maintains a fitness regimen and is extremely sensitive to sound even when asleep. His military mannerisms are also apparent in the way he approaches his cases, some of the lingo he uses and his ability to remain calm even when under intense pressure,<ref name=\"SuperSEAL\">{{cite news|title=Five-0 Redux: The \u2018Super SEAL\u2019 effect|url=http://www.honolulupulse.com/2013/07/five-0-redux-super-seal/|work=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]]|date=July 20, 2013}}</ref> and he is frequently mocked by Danny for his lack of \"human\" touch. In later seasons he becomes more affable around the other task force members and would be seen cracking jokes with other team members.<ref name=\"S6E14\">{{cite episode |title=Hoa 'inea / Misery Loves Company|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 6)#ep132|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=February 12, 2016|season=6|number=14}}</ref> Despite his stoicism, he has a soft spot for children, especially his adoptive niece Joan and Danny's children Grace and Charlie, both of whom often refer to him as 'Uncle Steve', and is extremely protective of his younger sister [[List of Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series) characters#Mary Ann McGarrett|Mary]].<ref>{{cite episode |title=Kalele / Faith|episodelink=Hawaii Five-O (2010 TV series, season 2)|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=March 19, 2012|season=2|number=19}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode |title=Ke Kinohi / The Beginning|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 1)#ep13|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=January 3, 2011|season=1|number=13}}</ref>\n\nMuch of McGarrett's interaction with Danny outside of work usually begins and ends with the duo bickering over trivial matters or good-naturedly mocking one another; there is a running gag in the show where various characters would comment on how the duo bicker like an \"old married couple\". Although they seem like polar opposites\u2014for example, McGarrett keeps his house neat and tidy and keeps his emotions bottled up while Danny is shown to be a slob<ref>{{cite episode |title=Kupale / Defender|episodelink=Hawaii Five-O (2010 TV series, season 2)|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=February 20, 2012|season=2|number=17}}</ref> and often vocalizes his frustrations by ranting\u2014they form an unlikely friendship, with McGarrett mocking Danny in his deadpan humor several times about how the latter misses him secretly but refuses to admit it. Although he is often referred to as \"Boss\" by the other members of Five-0 and he is usually seen giving orders, he considers the other members of the team as his peers and ''ohana'' (family), as mentioned in the [[Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 5)|Season 5]] premiere.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\nMcGarrett was in a long-term on-and-off relationship with Catherine Rollins ([[Michelle Borth]]), a rekindled old flame introduced early in [[Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 1)|season 1]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/business/mcgarretts-romantic-tumble-fails-to-keep-five-0-in-lead/|title=McGarrett's romantic tumble fails to keep \u2018Five-0\u2019 in lead|accessdate=May 17, 2016|date=October 20, 2010|work=[[Honolulu Star Advertiser]]|author=Gordon, Mike}}</ref> Early in [[Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 6)|season 6]], she leaves on a classified [[CIA]] operation before he's able to propose to her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/features/five-0-redux/calm-before-storm/|title=Calm before the storm|accessdate=May 18, 2016|date=October 10, 2015|work=[[Honolulu Star Advertiser]]|author=Burbridge, Wendie}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/features/five-0-redux/changing-the-plan/|title=Changing the plan|accessdate=May 17, 2016|date=October 17, 2015|work=[[Honolulu Star Advertiser]]|author=Burbridge, Wendie}}</ref> He begins to date Lynn ([[Sarah Carter]]) later that season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/features/five-0-redux/a-killer-first-date/|title=A killer first date|accessdate=May 17, 2016|date=November 7, 2015|work=[[Honolulu Star Advertiser]]|last=Burbridge|first=Wendie}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/features/five-0-redux/falling-in-love-again/|title=Falling in love again|accessdate=May 17, 2016|date=February 13, 2016|work=[[Honolulu Star Advertiser]]|author=Burbridge, Wendie}}</ref>\n\nMcGarrett is an extremely private man who rarely shares aspects of his personal life or preferences, in contrast to Danny, who rants about anything and everything he dislikes. For example, he attempted to keep his relationship with Catherine a secret from the team for much of season 1, although Danny later stated that he knew whenever Catherine was in town from McGarrett's \"stupid smile\". Although used to working in a team environment, he is usually a \"lone wolf\" who is extremely self-reliant and has difficulty relying on others for emotional support, which was a source of concern for his Aunt Deb.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/features/five-0-redux/giving-life-and-love/|title=Giving life and love|accessdate=May 17, 2016|date=January 16, 2016|work=[[Honolulu Star Advertiser]]|last=Burbridge|first=Wendie}}</ref> Despite Danny's persistent prying, McGarrett never speaks of his military service, largely because of the classified nature of most of his missions, often brushing Danny off with \"It's classified\" or \"[[Glomar response|I can neither confirm nor deny]]\". He frequently displays little or no emotion in situations where Danny is extremely emotional. It is not until Season 5 that McGarrett finally explains to Danny that he was raised in a family environment where males were not encouraged to express emotion.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Kuka\u02bbawale / Stakeout|episodelink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 5)#ep110|series=Hawaii Five-0|serieslink=Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series)|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=February 27, 2015|season=5|number=17}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and decorations===\nThe following are the awards and decorations worn by Lt. Cmdr. McGarrett in [[Hawaii Five-0 (2010 TV series, season 7)|Season 7 Episode 22 - Waimaka 'ele'ele]].\n\n{| style=\"width=100%;\"\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" |\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=2 |'''Personal decorations'''\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Silver Star ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Silver Star]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|other_device=v|ribbon=Bronze Star ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Bronze Star Medal]], w/[[Valor device|V Device]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Purple Heart ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Purple Heart]], w/1 gold award star (2 awards)\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Joint Service Commendation ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Commendation Medal#Joint Service|Joint Service Commendation Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=2|type=award-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Commendation ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Commendation Medal#Navy, Marine Corps and Coast Guard|Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]], w/2 gold award stars (3 awards)\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Us jointservachiev rib.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Achievement Medal#Joint Service|Joint Service Achievement Medal]], w/1 bronze oak leaf cluster (2 awards)\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Achievement ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Combat Action Ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Combat Action Ribbon]], w/1 gold award star (2 awards)\n|-  style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=2 |'''Unit awards'''\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=United States Navy Presidential Unit Citation ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Navy Presidential Unit Citation]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|name=Joint Meritorious Unit Award-3d|width=60}}\n|[[Joint Meritorious Unit Award]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Navy Unit Commendation]]\n|-  style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=2 |'''Service Awards'''\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Fleet Marine Force Ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Fleet Marine Force Ribbon]]\n|-  style=\"background:#ccf; text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=2 